message.raw:
Redefined a generic line tokenizer to construct the byte offsets for any
type of XML file, regardless of white space.


Added an IndexedXML base class for later byte offset indexed XML file readers
This type supplies no new public methods, but redefines internally how :meth:`get_by_id`
functions, using a fast look up when the id is in the offset index, and falling back to the
normal behavior when an index is not available.

Added an IndexedMzIdentML class inheriting from MzIdentML and IndexedXML. This class builds an
Index for a subset of the elements used by reference in the parsing process to speed up parsing.

In order to justify the process, I compared the performance of the IndexedMzIdentML parser with the
base MzIdentML parser with in-memory caching of lxml.Elements turned on, and speeds were comparable,
but with a 33% reduction in memory consumption. Tuning of the elements which are indexed could produce
is replaced by an instance of an Indexed derived class.
I believe that the current implementation passes all unit tests for existing features when the base parser

message.raw:
Added an IndexedMzML class to make random access of indexed MzML documents possible.

New class is derived from the original mzml.MzML reader, with a modified __init__ method
to build up a byte offset index for spectra relative to the start of the file. If applied
to a non-indexed MzML file, the class will fall back on its parent class methods with no
loss of functionality, but without the substantial improvement in random access performance
by `get_by_id`. As a convenience notation, I also set the __getitem__ method on the INdexedMzML
class to invoke `get_by_id` as the interface makes sense given the behavior, but this asymmetry
with the base class may not be worth the saved characters.

Added an IndexedMzML class to make random access of indexed MzML documents possible.

New class is derived from the original mzml.MzML reader, with a modified __init__ method
to build up a byte offset index for spectra relative to the start of the file. If applied
to a non-indexed MzML file, the class will fall back on its parent class methods with no
loss of functionality, but without the substantial improvement in random access performance
by `get_by_id`. As a convenience notation, I also set the __getitem__ method on the INdexedMzML
class to invoke `get_by_id` as the interface makes sense given the behavior, but this asymmetry
with the base class may not be worth the saved characters.
